{"id":"1507.07468","submitter":"Ines de Vega","authors":"Ines de Vega, Ulrich Schollw\\\"ock and F. Alexander Wolf","title":"How to discretize a quantum bath for real-time evolution","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 92, 155126 (2015)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.92.155126","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Many numerical techniques for the description of quantum systems that are\ncoupled to a continuous bath require the discretization of the latter. To this\nend, a wealth of methods has been developed in the literature, which we\nclassify as (i) direct discretization, (ii) orthogonal polynomial, and (iii)\nnumerical optimization strategies. We recapitulate strategies (i) and (ii) to\nclarify their relation. For quadratic Hamiltonians, we show that (ii) is the\nbest strategy in the sense that it gives the numerically exact time evolution\nup to a maximum time $t_\\text{max}$, for which we give a simple expression. For\nnon-quadratic Hamiltonians, we show that no such best strategy exists. We\npresent numerical examples relevant to open quantum systems and strongly\ncorrelated systems, as treated by dynamical mean-field theory (DMFT).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 27 Jul 2015 16:05:51 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 21 Oct 2015 14:05:34 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-10-22"}
